In the [Asserts Module documentation](http://codeception.com/docs/modules/Asserts#assertGreaterThan), it is claimed that when using `assertGreaterThan($expected, $actual)`, the expression `$expected > $actual` should evaluate to `true`. The order of parameters is the same for `assertGreaterThanOrEqual`, `assertLessThan`, and `assertLessThanOrEqual`.

However, this is the opposite of actual functionality, as documented in [PHPUnit](https://phpunit.de/manual/current/en/appendixes.assertions.html). This can be tested with the following Cest code:

    public function test_asserts(ApiTester $I)
    {   
        $I->assertLessThan(2,1);
        $I->assertLessThanOrEqual(2,1);

        $I->assertGreaterThan(1,2);
        $I->assertGreaterThanOrEqual(1,2);
    }

Each of these pass, although they contradict the documentation.

Given the fact that `@dataProvider` test methods can't be used with the `@depends` annotation, I'm currently using a property (array) to which I add all of the data I want to use in the next test. I'm using the `_before` and `_after` hooks to mock some stuff, only to find that I have to call it manually in the second test case (the one with the `@after` annotation).

An example to replicate this behavior/issue:

```php
<?php
use Codeception\TestCase\Test;

class SimpleTest extends Test
{
    /**
     * @var array
     */
    protected $tempArr = array();

    /**
     * @var \DateTime
     */
    protected $mocked = null;

    protected function _before()
    {
        $this->mocked = new DateTime();
    }

    /**
     * @param string $string
     * @dataProvider fooProvider
     */
    public function testFoo($string)
    {
        if ($string{0} === strtolower($string{0})) {
            $this->tempArr[] = $string;
        }
        $this->assertInstanceOf('\DateTime', $this->mocked);
    }

    /**
     * @after testFoo
     */
    public function testBar()
    {
        foreach ($this->tempArr as $string) {
            $this->assertFalse(
                $string === strtoupper($string)
            );
        }
        $this->assertInstanceOf('\DateTime', $this->mocked);//<== FAILS
    }

    /**
     * @return array
     */
    public function fooProvider()
    {
        return array(
            array(
                'string'
            ),
            array(
                'String'
            )
        );
    }

    protected function _after()
    {
        $this->mocked = null;
    }
}
```

